Whoever uses the app helps to trace and break the chain of infection. The app saves encounters with other persons locally on your smartphone. You are notified if you have encountered persons who were later confirmed with a SARS-CoV-2 infection. Your identity and privacy are always protected.

The National Institute of Public Health (NIJZ) is the central institution for health protection in Slovenia. The NIJZ provides professional or content support to the application managed and maintained by the Ministry of Public Administration of the Republic of Slovenia. In addition to strict adherence to measures to prevent SARS-CoV-2 infection, the spread of the disease can be further limited by using the application.
A group of persons use their smartphones around town.
If you have any questions about the #OstaniZdrav App contact the Single Contact Centre. If you need psychological support, contact the psychological support hotline.

Languages: Slovene and English
Business hours: Monday to Sunday: 8am - 8pm
The call is free of charge.
For calls from abroad: +386 1 478 7557
General information on COVID-19 is available on the website of the National Institute of Public Health and the Ministry of Health.
For psychological support during the COVID-19 epidemic please call 080 51 00, available 24 hours a day and 7 days a week and free of charge.

More on the #OstaniZdrav App. You will be forwarded to an external web site.

The #OstaniZdrav App was prepared by the National Institute of Public Health and the Ministry of Public Administration, where the Institute is responsible for the content of the application and the Ministry for the technical part. Both are therefore common data controllers of the data processed for the #OstaniZdrav App.
A hand holds a smartphone displaying a large body of text on the screen. Next to the text is a section symbol representing the imprint.
A woman uses the #OstaniZdrav App on her smartphone. An icon showing a padlock on the background of a shield symbolizes encrypted data.

Several countries are working together to enable transnational alerts via a joint exchange server. For example, contacts with users of an official coronavirus app from other participating countries can also be taken into account for exposure logging.

The app’s privacy notice (including information about the data processing carried out for the transnational exposure logging feature) can be found in the menu under “App Information” > “Data Privacy”.
The following countries currently participate in transnational exposure logging:

To do this, the app downloads a list, which is updated daily, of the random IDs of all users who have shared their random IDs via their own app. This list is then compared with the random IDs recorded by your smartphone.
A hand holds a smartphone. Europe and the European flag are illustrated in the background.
The terms of use have also been updated, to reflect the functional enhancements in the app.

The Terms of Use and Privacy Policy can also be found in the menu under “App Information” and in the app description in your app store. The changes will not affect how you use the app. If you continue to use the app or reopen it, we will assume that you agree to the updated Terms of Use.

The features of the #OstaniZdrav have been enhanced. Many countries have joined up to enable international warnings, based on a jointly-operated exchange server. Exposure to users of official corona apps in other participating countries can now be taken into account when calculating your exposure risk.

Several countries have teamed up to enable transnational warnings. In other words, your potential exposure to users of the official coronavirus apps in all participating countries can now be taken into account.
You can view the participating countries in the exposure logging details.
Your Internet connection may have been lost. Please ensure that you are connected to the Internet.
For more information about the #OstaniZdrav App please visit gov.si
Exposure log data is retrieved and synchronized with reported infections of other users.
Encounters over an extended period and in close proximity to a person with a confirmed SARS-CoV-2 infection.

Random IDs are combinations of digits and letters generated randomly. They are exchanged between devices in close proximity. Random IDs cannot be traced to a specific person and are automatically deleted after 14 days. Persons with a confirmed infection with SARS-CoV-2 can opt to share their random IDs of up to the last 14 days with other app users.
The display of exposures in the #OstaniZdrav App.
List of received and temporary random IDs saved temporarily in the operating system storage. This list is read when the exposures are checked. All random IDs are automatically deleted after 14 days.

If you have had contact within the last 14 days with a person who has a confirmed SARS-CoV-2 infection, the app evaluates your personal risk of infection. It does this by measuring duration and proximity of the exposure
Another central feature is anonimously sharing your positive test result. If you have a confirmed SARS-CoV-2 infection, you can notify others and break the chain of infection.
Exposure logging is one of three central features of the app. Once you activate it, encounters with people\'s smartphones are logged. You don\'t have to do anything else.

Turn your smartphone into a novel coronavirus (SARS-CoV-2) warning system. Infection with this virus can cause the COVID-19 disease or pass without any symptoms. Get an overview of your risk status and find out whether you\'ve had close contact with anyone confirmed with a SARS-CoV-2 infection in the last 14 days.
The app logs encounters between individuals by exchanging encrypted, random IDs between their devices, whereby no personal data whatsoever is accessed.

Enable prioritised background activity to allow the App to determine your risk status in the background any time (recommended). This disables battery life optimisation for the #OstaniZdrav App only. We do not expect this to cause a significant decrease in your device\'s battery life. If you do not allow this setting, we recommend you to open the App manually at least once every 24 hours.
A group of persons use their smartphones around town.

Please note that with prioritized background activity disabled, you have to open the app manually at least once every 24 hours to update your risk status.\n\nYou can enable prioritized background activity in your settings any time.

A woman uses the #OstaniZdrav App on her smartphone. An icon showing a padlock on the background of a shield symbolizes encrypted data.
More protection for you and for us all. By using the #OstaniZdrav App we can break infection chains much quicker.
Onboarding page 4 of 5: If you have a confirmed infection with SARS-CoV-2...

Your notification is encrypted securely and processed on a secure server. People whose encrypted random IDs your smartphone has collected will now receive a warning along with information about what they should now do.
If you have a confirmed SARS-CoV-2 infection...
An encrypted positive test diagnosis is transmitted to the system, which will now warn other users.
… please report this in the #OstaniZdrav App. Sharing information of a SARS-CoV-2 infection is voluntary and secure. Please do this for the sake of everyone\'s health.
Onboarding page 3 of 6: How to Enable Exposure Logging

Exposure logging works by your smartphone receiving, via Bluetooth, encrypted random IDs of other users and passing your own random IDs to their smartphones. Exposure logging can be deactivated at any time.

The encrypted random IDs only pass information about date, duration, and proximity (calculated from signal strength) to other people. Personal data as in name, address and location are not being logged or exchanged. Individuals cannot be identified based on the random IDs.
This means the #OstaniZdrav App cannot send or receive notifications about your SARS-CoV-2 infection risk status. You can deactivate this feature at any time.
